            <p>
                We start with three results from Fermat's theorem:
                <md>
                    <mrow> a^3 \amp \equiv a \pmod{3} </mrow>
                    <mrow> a^7 \amp \equiv a \pmod{7} </mrow>
                    <mrow> a^{13} \amp \equiv a \pmod{13}. </mrow>
                </md>

                From the first:
                <md>
                    a^{13} \equiv (a^3)^4\cdot a \equiv a^5 \equiv a^3 \cdot a^2 \equiv a \cdot a^2 \equiv a   \pmod{3}. 
                </md>

                From the second:
                <md>
                    a^{13} \equiv a^7 \cdot a^6 \equiv a \cdot a^6 \equiv a^7 \equiv a \pmod{7}.
                </md>

                The third doesn't need any extra work.  Use the lemma from class to combine:

                <md>
                    a^{13} \equiv a \pmod{3\cdot 7 \cdot 13}.
                </md>
                
                
                
