<subsection xml:id="Question_5_2_9">
     <title>Problem 9</title>  
<p>
    This question illustrates an alternative to the Eucldian algorithm for finding an initial solution to a linear congruence.
</p>

<p>
    If <m>\text{gcd}(a,p)=1</m> then <m>a^{p-1}\equiv 1 \pmod{p}.</m>
    Multiply both sides of the linear congruence by <m>a^{p-2}:</m>
    <md>
        <mrow>ax  \amp \equiv b \pmod{p} </mrow>
        <mrow> a\cdot a^{p-2} x \amp \equiv a^{p-2} b \pmod{p}</mrow>
        <mrow>a^{p-1} x \amp \equiv a^{p-2} b \pmod{p} </mrow>
        <mrow> x \amp \equiv a^{p-2} b \pmod{p} </mrow>
    </md>
    
</p>
<p>
    We'll illustrate with one of the linear congruences. The others are similar.
    For <m>6x \equiv 5 \pmod{11}</m> we need to compute <m>5 \cdot 6^{9} \pmod{11}.</m>
    <md>
        <mrow> 6^2 \amp \equiv 36 \equiv 3 \pmod{11} </mrow>
        <mrow> 6^4 \amp \equiv 3 \cdot 3 \equiv 9 \pmod{11}</mrow>
        <mrow> 6^8 \amp \equiv 81 \equiv 4 \pmod{11} </mrow>
        <mrow> 6^9 \amp \equiv 6^8\cdot 6 \equiv 24 \equiv 2 \pmod{11} </mrow>
        <mrow> 5 \cdot 6^9  \amp \equiv 10 \pmod{11}.</mrow>
    </md>

    It is easy to check: <m>6\cdot 10 -5=55</m> which is divisible by 11.
    
</p>
</subsection>

